bug.short_desc: Adding a preprocessor symbol erases previously defined ones

long_desc.thetext:
CDT HEAD
To reproduce: 1. Click on Add button in Project Properties->C/C++ General->Paths and Symbols->Symbols->GNU C++ and add symbol S1 with the value s1. 2. Click on Add button again and add symbol S2 with the value s2.
Notice that the previously defined S1 disappears from the list.
Bumped up severity since this bug is very annoying. I have to edit .cproject file by hand to work around it.

Created attachment 94714 What I do wrong ?
Sergey,
I still cannot reproduce the problem, neither with Eclipse M5 (+ CDT Head), nor with pre-M6. Symbols are added correctly.
Could you please provide some additional info: - does it occur with all projects, or... ? - does .log file contain anything ? - when the problem occured first ? I mean, which code was used ? - does the problem persist with today's CDT code ?

(In reply to comment #3) > Created an attachment (id=94714) [details] > What I do wrong ? > > > Sergey, > > I still cannot reproduce the problem, > neither with Eclipse M5 (+ CDT Head), > nor with pre-M6. > Symbols are added correctly. > > Could you please provide some additional info: > - does it occur with all projects, or... ?
Weird stuff happens in all projects, but the behavior differs project from project. On a freshly created Makefile/Other toolchain project on Linux an attempt to set __GNUC__ = 4 results in no symbol being set. A quick inspection of .cproject file shows a rather large <option id="org.eclipse.cdt.build.core.settings.holder.undef.symbols.1438533551" name="Undefined Symbols" superClass="org.eclipse.cdt.build.core.settings.holder.undef.symbols" valueType="undefDefinedSymbols"> section containing among other things <listOptionValue builtIn="false" value="__GNUC__"/>
In a project created using a custom project wizard with a custom toolchain adding a new symbol to the definedSymbols section adds all previously defined symbols to the undefDefinedSymbols section as a side effect.
Shouldn't the behavior be quite the opposite? It would make sense if adding a symbol to definedSymbols would remove that symbol from undefDefinedSymbols, wouldn't it?
> - does .log file contain anything ?
No
> - when the problem occurred first ? I mean, which code was used ?
Not sure. Could be as old as 4.0.
> - does the problem persist with today's CDT code ?
Latest tests done with CDT 5.0 M6
The problem with undefined symbols was fixed (bug #224769) in CDT Head and cdt4_0 branch last Friday. Let's try, may be your problem has the same origin.

(In reply to comment #5) > The problem with undefined symbols was fixed (bug #224769) > in CDT Head and cdt4_0 branch last Friday. > Let's try, may be your problem has the same origin.
Nothing has visibly changed in CDT I200804070803. Oleg, you should be able to reproduce the part of the bug related to Makefile/Other toolchain project. It's very easy. Make sure that you try to define __GNUC__ variable and not a variable with some arbitrary name.
The whole concept of undefDefinedSymbols seems very strange. Do you know what it is used for?

> Make sure that you try to define > __GNUC__ variable and not a > variable with some arbitrary name.
Thanks. Reproduced with __GNUC__ Work is in progress.
> The whole concept of undefDefinedSymbols > seems very strange. Do you know what > it is used for?
Initially, it was added to screen out unwanted built-in values, for example include paths or preprocessor symbols, detected by scanner discovery mechanism.

Root cause: it's impossible now to add user's symbol with the same name as for system symbol, regardless of different symbol value.
Fix will be appled after additional testing, because there's a risk to break other functionality.
Workarond for now: use Properties -> C/C++ Build -> Settings -> Tool Settings -> Your Compiler -> Symbols. The same for reactivation of wrongly undefined symbols.

(In reply to comment #7)
> Initially, it was added to screen out unwanted > built-in values, for example include paths or > preprocessor symbols, detected by scanner > discovery mechanism.
Few questions: 1. What does "unwanted" mean and who determines if a symbol is wanted or unwanted? 2. Does scanner discovery still happen with "Other toolchain"? I don't think it should since it has no chance of producing meaningful results.

> 1. What does "unwanted" mean and who determines > if a symbol is wanted or unwanted?
This feature was introduced as answer to bug #178716: "No way to get rid of built-in includes" This bug was submitted by you, as I remember. You've asked includes only, but symbols and library paths are processed in the same way.
Who determines ? User, in ideal case. If some include path or preprocessor symbol (exported by discovery mechanism or somehow else) not needed, "Delete" button allows to get rid of it.
Sinse built-in symbols cannot be really deleted (they are exported by compiler each time, anyhow), "undefinintion" (-U) is used to remove them form environment on build time. On the other hand, Properties -> C/C++ Build -> Settings -> Tool Settings -> Compiler -> Symbols pane, with "Undefined" list, is a back-up way to restore deleted symbols. For undefined includes, use "Restore defaults" to remove undefined ones.
You know, currect code contains some bugs, so "undefined" symbols are produced wrongly. I'll try to eliminate this problem.
> Does scanner discovery still happen with "Other toolchain"?
For me (on Windows) it does not run with "Other".

Fixed in Head. Now user's symbols can overwrite built-in ones. No unexpected undefined symbols generated.
I've tried to test all possible cases, but something may be missed.
Feel free to reopen this bug or create new one if Paths & Symbols tabs behave strange. Please provide detailed info in this case: - which kind of project used - which language affected - which element (inc/symb) handled - what's exactly wrong - attach .cproject if possible.
Thanks in advance.

(In reply to comment #11) Thanks for the fix. I'll try it tomorrow.
It seems that handling of defined and undefined symbols was only part of the problem. The other part is that Other toolchain tries to do scanner discovery on Linux. I'll create a separate bug for that.
Filed bug 226419 for the scanner discovery issue.

Still doesn't work in the following scenario:
1. On Linux create a Makefile/Other Toolchain project with everything by default. 2. Open Symbols tab in project properties, select GNU C++, Click Add, type __GNUC__ for name and 4 for value and click OK.
The symbol does not get added. Examination of .cproject file shows that the symbol is not there. Nothing gets logged to the error log.

To clarify:
attempt to add symbol with the same name and same value as existing one - does nothing. The same for include paths: path equal to one of exising paths cannot be added.
As Sergey says, symbols with another values (different to existing) are added correctly. So it seems like problem is fixed.

(In reply to comment #15) > To clarify: > > attempt to add symbol with the same name > and same value as existing one - does nothing. > The same for include paths: path equal to one > of exising paths cannot be added. > > As Sergey says, symbols with another values > (different to existing) are added correctly. > So it seems like problem is fixed.
I would argue that the current behavior is confusing and should be changed for the following three reasons: 1. Since built-in symbols are not shown by default, silent disappearance of a just entered symbol doesn't give user a clue what happened. 2. Current symbol filtering is not bullet proof. If I enter __GNUC__=5 and then change it to __GNUC__=4, it remains a user defined symbol in spite of the fact that there is the same built-in one. 3. Having a user-defined symbol with the same name and value as a built-in one is not equivalent to not having it, since the built-in symbols may change with a change of the compiler binary, but a user-defined one would maintain its value.
Thanks. I agree. Changes are made in Head. Now it's possible to overwrite system symbols.
Thanks a lot for fixing it.
